SIMPLE: exotic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exotic
<hw>Ex*ot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>exoticus</ets>, Gr. <?/ fr. <grk>'e`xw</grk> outside: cf. F.
<ets>exotique</ets>. See <er>Exoteric</er>.]</ety> <def>Introduced from
a foreign country; not native; extraneous; foreign; <as>as, an
<ex>exotic</ex> plant; an <ex>exotic</ex> term or word.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing was so splendid and <qex>exotic</qex> as the
ambassador.</q> <rj><qau>Evelyn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exotic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Exotic
<hw>Ex*ot"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anything of foreign
origin; something not of native growth, as a plant, a word, a
custom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Plants that are unknown to Italy, and such as the gardeners call
<qex>exotics</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exotical</ent>⟦br⟧
